    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim._with({ win = vim.api.nvim_get_current_win() }, vim.cmd.tabnew)` results in rendering issues: cursor is left on top of the tabline.\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim --clean`\n2. `:lua vim._with({ win = vim.api.nvim_get_current_win() }, vim.cmd.tabnew)`. Cursor is left on top of the tabline. Starting to insert text removes the tabline, while executing `gt` returns everything to normal.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNo rendering issues.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-221+g39410ef42b\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 6.19.11-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.3.1-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I suppose this is technically a Vim bug, as `switch_win_noblock` with `no_display` skips updating `tp_old_Rows_avail`, calling `win_new_screen_rows` and other side-effects you typically get from `leave`/`enter_tabpage`.\n\nE.g:\n\n```vim\ncall win_execute(win_getid(), 'tabnew')\n```",
